message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
title: "Selective Permeability: A Behavioral-Security Metric for LLM Advisors, with Two Failure Modes of In-Context Provenance Workflows"
abstract: >-
  A behavioral-security study of seven frontier / near-frontier LLM advisors that measures a two-sided
  "selective permeability" (update-on-authorized minus leak-on-illegitimate) and re-operationalizes
  experimental-psychology procedures as adversarial assays. Crude social pressure, forged tokens and
  factual opinion-flip crack only weaker-aligned models; subtle credential attacks (a benign token
  request; handing over the real authorization lever when it is labeled "routine") crack even the
  frontier. A label-vs-referent dissociation (W7d) shows refusal posture tracks the secrecy label, not the
  token's actual authority. Two under-tested failure modes of in-context bearer-token provenance workflows
  are identified: credential disclosure/forgery and summarization-induced source amnesia.
type: report
